<Project slug="iso27001-gap-analysis">
  <p class="lead">
    Most ISO 27001 gap analysis templates jump straight to the 93 Annex A
    controls. That misses what the standard actually requires and this is what an
    external auditor would look for first.
  </p>

  <h2>The problem I wanted to solve</h2>
  <p>
    ISO 27001 is a management system standard. Clauses 4 through 10 define the
    governance backbone that makes the controls work. A gap analysis that ignores
    these clauses produces a tidy spreadsheet but tells you very little about
    whether the organisation can actually operate an ISMS. I wanted to build a gap
    analysis that an external auditor would recognise as professional work, and not just a checklist.
  </p>

  <h2>How I approached it</h2>

  <h3>Scope first</h3>
  <p>
    <strong>Clause 4.3</strong> mandates that you define the boundaries of your
    ISMS before doing anything else. For PayWave, I scoped the digital payment
    platform, mobile app, merchant portal and supporting IT infrastructure at the
    One-North office, and explicitly excluded the marketing systems and the
    staging environment with documented justification. The scope sounds bureaucratic,
    but it drives every subsequent decision about which controls apply and what
    evidence is needed.
  </p>

  <h3>Then the management clauses</h3>
  <p>
    I worked through Clauses 4 to 10, assessing what PayWave had in place and
    where it fell short.
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li>Clause&nbsp;4 (Context) — partial: a scope statement exists but no formal context analysis.</li>
    <li>Clause&nbsp;5 (Leadership) — partial: a CISO is in place but no board reporting cadence.</li>
    <li>Clause&nbsp;6 (Planning) — gap: no documented risk assessment methodology.</li>
  </ul>
  <div class="callout">
    <span class="section-mark">Why this matters</span>
    <p>
      That last finding — no documented methodology under
      <span class="cite">ISO 27001 §6.1.2</span> — directly drove my second
      portfolio project. The risk register exists because this clause requires it.
      The artefacts cross-reference each other by design.
    </p>
  </div>

  <h3>Annex A, sampled deliberately</h3>
  <p>
    Only then did I move to Annex A. I sampled 26 controls across all four themes
    (Organisational, People, Physical, Technological); enough to demonstrate
    methodology without producing an unreadable document. For each control, I
    assessed implementation status, assigned a 1–5 maturity score against a
    defined model, collected evidence references and documented the specific gap.
    Generic findings like "needs improvement" are useless; I wrote findings like
    "No EDR on endpoints; CloudWatch monitors infrastructure only; no behavioural
    analysis."
  </p>

  <h3>The Statement of Applicability</h3>
  <p>
    This is where I spent the most time. <strong>Clause 6.1.3(d)</strong> requires
    the SoA as a mandatory document, and auditors examine it line by line. For
    every control, I wrote a justification grounded in specific regulatory
    references — not generic "compliance" language. For A.5.3 (Segregation of
    duties) my justification reads: "Required: critical for payment processing
    integrity. <span class="cite">PCI DSS Req 6.4</span> and
    <span class="cite">MAS TRM §9.2</span>." That level of citation is what
    separates a professional SoA from a templated one.
  </p>

  <h3>A phased remediation roadmap</h3>
  <p>
    Finally I produced a remediation roadmap with named owners, deadlines,
    measurable KPIs and budget estimates in Singapore dollars. With some background in project engineering, I am comfortable presenting a phased
    plan with dependencies and resource requirements that survives stakeholder scrutiny.
  </p>

  <h2>What I produced</h2>
  <p>
    A five-sheet Excel workbook covering the cover page, dashboard with
    auto-calculated metrics, gap analysis matrix, Statement of Applicability and
    risk register. Alongside it, a Word document containing a 12-month remediation
    roadmap with 22 specific actions, governance mechanisms and a SGD
    180,000–270,000 first-year budget estimate.
  </p>

  <h2>What this demonstrates</h2>
  <ul>
    <li>I understand ISO 27001 as a management system, not a checklist.</li>
    <li>I can apply an international standard within the Singapore regulatory context.</li>
    <li>I produce evidence-quality artefacts that would survive auditor scrutiny.</li>
    <li>The phased roadmap with budgets and named owners signals operational maturity.</li>
  </ul>
</Project>
